00:06:19.330 --> 00:06:20.330
10.

00:06:20.330 --> 00:06:23.870
The Joker
We finish with a twofold entry now, as this

00:06:23.870 --> 00:06:28.310
entry specifies the influence behind both
the comic book version of the Joker, and the

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:31.139
most iconic live action movie version of the
Joker.

00:06:31.139 --> 00:06:36.610
The story goes that a 17-year-old named Jerry
Robinson showed DC Comics' writer Bill Finger

00:06:36.610 --> 00:06:39.509
a Joker playing card he'd drawn up from memory.

00:06:39.509 --> 00:06:43.849
Finger then suggested they supplement this
"sinister clown" with the creepy permanent

00:06:43.849 --> 00:06:48.819
grin featured in a silent movie called The
Man Who Laughs - a movie in which Conrad Veidt

00:06:48.819 --> 00:06:53.629
played a man whose face has been disfigured
so it looks like he's grinning from ear-to-ear.

00:06:53.629 --> 00:06:58.530
The resemblence to the Joker is undoubtedly
uncanny, so he's not as original as some people

00:06:58.530 --> 00:06:59.530
might think.

00:06:59.530 --> 00:07:03.789
Finally, we come to Heath Ledger's version
of the character from 2008's The Dark Knight.

00:07:03.789 --> 00:07:07.430
The Oscar-winning portrayal took influence
from a number of sources.

00:07:07.430 --> 00:07:12.020
Ledger's voice and mannerisms were mainly
inspired by musician and actor Tom Waites,

00:07:12.020 --> 00:07:16.629
but Ledger also took influence from musician
Sid Vicious and actor Malcolm McDowell's portrayal

00:07:16.629 --> 00:07:18.490
of Alex DeLarge in A Clockwork Orange.

